@Steve L 

Sometimes you have to tailor your answers accordingly.



!!!

@john ezra 

Talk about a cliffhanger!  It’s Holy Week, I gave up bourbon for lent, and I need to know this joke. 

I tried googling those hints but got nowhere fun.  Damn!

@Steve L 

I had no idea that Chevy  manufactured a car called BOLT. I was stuck on VOLT for too long, because I was so sure that was the answer. But I also knew that I had to BOLT out of Dodge. So there was a lot of head-scratching until I finally scribbled that B.

At least they learned from their Spanish error of long ago and didn't name it NOVA.

@Times Rita 

The story that Chevy couldn't sell the Nova in Latin America was apocryphal.  The word nova, in the astronomical sense, exists in Spanish, and no one was confused.  Also, va in Spanish would not be the normal verb used in such a construction; it would normally be "no sirve" or "no funciona".

Imagine a furniture store named "Notable Furnishings".  Would you assume you couldn't buy a dining room set there because they had no table?

@Tristan 

In British English, it is STOReY, but American English uses STORY. 

As for PLURAL, you are correct that it is vague for a Tuesday, but hopefully you can now be on the lookout for that type of thing, and it will help in future puzzles.

@Tristan 

Far more Americans speak a bit--or a lot--of Spanish than a bit or a lot of Tagalog.  Remember that it's an American puzzle, mostly for American solvers, although we welcome others with open arms.

I would agree that this was a more challenging Tuesday than most, but I think a little extra difficulty from time to time is a good thing.

@Anatol 

Since there is no other place this is indeed the place to talk about the mini.  I've waged a campaign in the past to ask that Mini threads (they are very slender, y'know) include a spoiler alert but got voted down so now I just scroll quickly past.  

In my background (ag, horticulture, turf) soil with a pH below 7 is acidic and above is alkaline.   Keeps things simple.

@Steve L 

I pronounce it with a short E, though the dictionary tells me that a schwa is acceptable. 

Either way, “hominem” is not quite a homophone for homonym. I didn’t realize until I read the column that that’s how the revealer is supposed to work. But it’s a minor problem for an otherwise fine puzzle.

@Eric Hougland 

I see that the dictionaries try to make a distinction, but I believe that in my ideolect, at least, the two words are pronounced basically the same.

When I was in elementary school, I noticed that dictionaries said that the names of the days of the week were pronounced with the same final syllable as "tardy" or "handy".  And yet, I (and everyone I knew), pronounced the last syllable as "day", clear as day.  "Sundy" always sounded peculiar to me.  It was then that I realized that the dictionaries don't always capture the speech patterns of every native speaker.

@Eric Hougland -- Re: Remembering puzzles for POY nominations:

When last year I did remember Lewis and Jeff's jaw-dropping NAME DROPPING puzzle, but couldn't -- and still can't -- remember a wonderful puzzle by two women constructors (if I remembered who, I could have Googled it) that had something to do with switching words in the grid from left to right or right to left or something like that and that was quite ingenious and that I absolutely loved and would have nominated if only I'd remembered it, I resolved to keep a running list from then on.

It's nice to know, Eric, that at least one other person here is similarly puzzle-memory-challenged:)

@ad absurdum 
When I served roast beef for dinner, I had to METE meat.

(Surprised that you're not going by AD HOMINEM today.)

@ad absurdum - tutti is accented on the first syllable; tutee on the second. If tutti is pronounced correctly, there is a hesitation after closing the first t of the pair before releasing it for the second t.

Nearly all of our suffixive English -ee words are accented on the suffix
alienee, escapee, mentee, tutee, conferee, referee,

@v 

As an American, I cannot understand why you'd think it isn't.  Although there are supposedly slight differences in the pronunciation of the last vowel (which I don't even hear), they'd have to be vastly different for you not to understand why we think they're similar.

So how would you pronounce it?

@Steve L 

I have no idea how to write down what it sounds like in Polish, but it really is a very different pronunciation than Add homonym. I can imagine it would be the same in any other Slavic language, as well as German, Italian, and probably many others.

Let me try: add (the a being the same as in cArramba, so not the same as in the American add) ho (as in horror), mee (as in meeting) nem (as in enema).

@Anne Perlmutter - Argumentum ad hominem is literally one of the most widely known logical fallacies. Also one of the most misunderstood. 

I think you need a more complete dictionary. 






EMUs never argue ad hominem.

